<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>T 444E Diesel Engine Diagnostics (1997) - SECTION 3.5: CIRCUIT FUNCTION AND DIAGNOSTICS - BAROMETRIC
        PRESSURE (BARO) SENSOR - FAULT DETECTION/MANAGEMENT
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="1">
        <title>FAULT DETECTION/MANAGEMENT</title>
        <para>A BARO signal that is detected out of range high or low by the ECM will cause the ECM to ignore the BARO
            signal and use the Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) signal generated at low idle as an indication of
            barometric pressure. If a MAP fault is detected, the BARO will default to 29.6 in. Hg. of barometric
            pressure.
        </para>
        <para>Refer to
            <emph type="bold">Figure
                <hotlnk xrefid="ef1251808">3.15</hotlnk>
            </emph>
            and
            <emph type="bold">Table
                <hotlnk xrefid="et1251802">3.7</hotlnk>
            </emph>
            for the circuit diagram and table of the Barometric Pressure Sensor (BARO).
        </para>
        <figure id="ef1251808" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="eg7019" filename="../figeg7/eg7019.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 3.15 - Barometric Pressure Sensor Circuit Diagram</caption>
        </figure>
